1. a. The name did not corne from Gerbert’s letters.

In the xivth and xvth centuries the readers of Gerbert's letters must have been rare. That was a period os reviving interest in the classical writers of Greece and Rome; if the letters of Gerbert were read, it was by ecclesiastics. There is not much in thern of general or literary interest. Copies too were not likely to be easily procurable. The period of Gerbert belongs to one of the darkest times of the Middle Age. From such writings the xivth and xvth centuries turned away with increasing indifference. Yet, suppose a man like Poggio coming to the knowledge of the isolated passage in Gerbert’s letters where M. Manlius de astrologia is mentioned, he would have taken not only the name of the author, but the title of his work as he found it. But Gerbert calls the work de Astrologz'a .· all MSS of the poem call it Astronomz‘con.
